## 🎯 Controller Patterns

### Standard Controller Structure
```typescript
@Controller('games')
@ApiTags('Games')
export class GamesController {
  constructor(private readonly gamesService: GamesService) {}

  @Post()
  @ApiOperation({ summary: 'Create a new game' })
  @ApiResponse({ status: 201, description: 'Game created successfully' })
  async create(@Body() createGameDto: CreateGameDto): Promise<GameResponseDto> {
    return this.gamesService.create(createGameDto);
  }
}
```

### Best Practices
- Keep controllers thin - delegate to services
- Use DTOs for all request/response bodies
- Document all endpoints with Swagger decorators
- Use appropriate HTTP status codes
- Handle exceptions at the filter level, not in controllers

## 🔧 Service Patterns

### Standard Service Structure
```typescript
@Injectable()
export class GamesService {
  constructor(
    @InjectRepository(GameEntity)
    private readonly gameRepository: Repository<GameEntity>,
    private readonly logger: LoggerService,
  ) {}

  async create(createGameDto: CreateGameDto): Promise<Game> {
    this.logger.log('Creating new game', { topic: createGameDto.topic });
    
    const game = this.gameRepository.create(createGameDto);
    return this.gameRepository.save(game);
  }
}
```

### Service Responsibilities
- Business logic implementation
- Data validation beyond DTO validation
- Database operations through repositories
- Error handling and logging
- Transaction management

## 🗄️ Entity Patterns

### TypeORM Entity Example
```typescript
@Entity('games')
export class GameEntity {
  @PrimaryGeneratedColumn('uuid')
  id: string;

  @Column()
  topic: string;

  @CreateDateColumn()
  createdAt: Date;

  @UpdateDateColumn()
  updatedAt: Date;
}
```

### Entity Best Practices
- Use UUIDs for primary keys when appropriate
- Always include `createdAt` and `updatedAt` timestamps
- Define relationships explicitly
- Use indexes for frequently queried fields
- Implement soft deletes when needed

